<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-06-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-06-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="920" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d920">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 868.001C76/10</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Chargé d’Affaires of
                                    Greece</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 1033</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Royal Legation of Greece</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="julian gregorian" when="1917-06-14">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 1/14, 1917</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary of State</hi>: Deeply moved, I have
                            the honor to inform your excellency that His Majesty King Constantin, my
                            august sovereign, yielding to insuperable political necessity upon steps
                            taken by three of the great Powers, is leaving Greece accompanied by Her
                            Majesty Queen Sophie and His Royal Highness Crown Prince George.</p>
                        <p>He leaves on the throne His Royal Highness Prince Alexander.</p>
                        <p>His Majesty the new King took yesterday the oath provided by the
                            Constitution.</p>
                        <p>The grief of the Greek people at their separation from a King to whom
                            they were devoted is unspeakable.</p>
                        <p>Be pleased to accept [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">A. Vouros</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>